<h3>Project Timeline &amp; Roadmap</h3>
<h4>Begin at the beginning &hellip;</h4>
[% FILTER html_para %]
At the end of November 2013 Jim Cheetham started the project,
by getting in touch with a couple of trusted contacts
to see if his idea for an Open solution for a hardware RNG was feasible.

Paul Campbell responsed enthuiastically, drafting hardware designs and
proposing a base component set based on his recent projects and a recently-purchased
<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SMT_placement_equipment">pick'n'place machine</a>.

Other contributions from people such as
<a href="http://iang.org/">Ian Grigg</a>
and <a href="https://www.cs.auckland.ac.nz/~pgut001/">Peter Gutmann</a>
were more crypto based, and provided a great set of ideal requirements
from their different perspectives. This helped us to realise at an early stage that we
didn't need to be a fully independent RNG, but should leave the final stages to external
software running in the OS. Sadly the project already had the name [% onerng %]
and I didn't fancy "One ENT" as a replacement!
[% END %]

<h4>Public announcement</h4>
[% FILTER html_para %]
Jim was at <a href="http://lca2014.linux.org.au/">LCA 2014</a> (linux.conf.au) in Perth
in early January 2014, and filled in a vacant slot in the Open Programming miniconf with
a quick (15 minutes over-running to 25!) presentation titled
<a href="http://mirror.linux.org.au/linux.conf.au/2014/Tuesday/143-A_Pseudo-Random_Talk_on_Entropy_-_Jim_Cheetham.mp4">A Pseudo-Random Talk on Entropy</a>.
This had a brief intro to [% onerng %] but the audience didn't take the bait!

Sadly I'd missed another miniconf presentation on a HWRNG by Paul Warren, but got him onto
our mailing list for future discussions.

I followed by announcing the [% onerng %] project to the whole LCA2014 community in the closing
<a href="http://mirror.linux.org.au/linux.conf.au/2014/Friday/122-LCA_2014_-_Lightning_Talks_pt2_and_Thanks.mp4">Lightning Talk session</a>
(at the 05:30 mark).
My friend Dan at <a href="http://onlinegroups.net/">OnlineGroups.net</a> contributed the
mailing-list/forum hosting that we needed, and our project was off and running!
[% END %]

<h4>Beta Units</h4>
[% FILTER html_para %]
By April 2014 Paul had produced the first hand-build beta units, and we started distributing them
to testers. By the end of July
<a href="http://arstechnica.com/security/2014/07/this-thumbdrive-hacks-computers-badusb-exploit-makes-devices-turn-evil/">BadUSB</a>
became a thing, and validated Paul's decision to do firmware updating only over a dedicated port
and not over USB at all!

Beta testing threw back a couple of broken devices, which helped to identify weak areas in the physical
design, and a few OS use-case problems.
[% END %]

